#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:2
msgid "Cache: working with cross-testrun state"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:8
msgid ""
"The functionality of this core plugin was previously distributed as a third "
"party plugin named ``pytest-cache``.  The core plugin is compatible "
"regarding command line options and API usage except that you can only store/"
"receive data between test runs that is json-serializable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:15
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:17
msgid ""
"The plugin provides two command line options to rerun failures from the last "
"``py.test`` invocation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:20
msgid "``--lf``, ``--last-failed`` - to only re-run the failures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:21
msgid ""
"``--ff``, ``--failed-first`` - to run the failures first and then the rest "
"of the tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:24
msgid ""
"For cleanup (usually not needed), a ``--cache-clear`` option allows to "
"remove all cross-session cache contents ahead of a test run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:27
msgid ""
"Other plugins may access the `config.cache`_ object to set/get **json "
"encodable** values between ``py.test`` invocations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:32
msgid ""
"This plugin is enabled by default, but can be disabled if needed: see :ref:"
"`cmdunregister` (the internal name for this plugin is ``cacheprovider``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:38
msgid "Rerunning only failures or failures first"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:40
msgid "First, let's create 50 test invocation of which only 2 fail::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:42
msgid ""
"# content of test_50.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"def test_num(i):\n"
"    if i in (17, 25):\n"
"       pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:50
msgid "If you run this for the first time you will see two failures::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:52
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q\n"
".................F.......F........................\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_num[17] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______ test_num[25] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"2 failed, 48 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:79
msgid "If you then run it with ``--lf``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:81
msgid ""
"$ py.test --lf\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"run-last-failure: rerun last 2 failures\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 50 items\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py FF\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_num[17] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______ test_num[25] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"======= 2 failed, 48 deselected in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:115
msgid ""
"You have run only the two failing test from the last run, while 48 tests "
"have not been run (\"deselected\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:118
msgid ""
"Now, if you run with the ``--ff`` option, all tests will be run but the "
"first previous failures will be executed first (as can be seen from the "
"series of ``FF`` and dots)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:122
msgid ""
"$ py.test --ff\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"run-last-failure: rerun last 2 failures first\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 50 items\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py FF................................................\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_num[17] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 17\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"_______ test_num[25] ________\n"
"\n"
"i = 25\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.mark.parametrize(\"i\", range(50))\n"
"    def test_num(i):\n"
"        if i in (17, 25):\n"
">          pytest.fail(\"bad luck\")\n"
"E          Failed: bad luck\n"
"\n"
"test_50.py:6: Failed\n"
"======= 2 failed, 48 passed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:159
msgid "The new config.cache object"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:163
msgid ""
"Plugins or conftest.py support code can get a cached value using the pytest "
"``config`` object.  Here is a basic example plugin which implements a :ref:"
"`fixture` which re-uses previously created state across py.test invocations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:168
msgid ""
"# content of test_caching.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"import time\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def mydata(request):\n"
"    val = request.config.cache.get(\"example/value\", None)\n"
"    if val is None:\n"
"        time.sleep(9*0.6) # expensive computation :)\n"
"        val = 42\n"
"        request.config.cache.set(\"example/value\", val)\n"
"    return val\n"
"\n"
"def test_function(mydata):\n"
"    assert mydata == 23"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:184
msgid ""
"If you run this command once, it will take a while because of the sleep::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:187 ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:204
msgid ""
"$ py.test -q\n"
"F\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_function ________\n"
"\n"
"mydata = 42\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function(mydata):\n"
">       assert mydata == 23\n"
"E       assert 42 == 23\n"
"\n"
"test_caching.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"1 failed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:201
msgid ""
"If you run it a second time the value will be retrieved from the cache and "
"this will be quick::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:218
msgid "See the `cache-api`_ for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:222
msgid "Inspecting Cache content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:224
msgid ""
"You can always peek at the content of the cache using the ``--cache-clear`` "
"command line option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:227
msgid ""
"$ py.test --cache-clear\n"
"======= test session starts ========\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.5.1, pytest-2.9.2, py-1.4.31, pluggy-0.3.1\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 1 items\n"
"\n"
"test_caching.py F\n"
"\n"
"======= FAILURES ========\n"
"_______ test_function ________\n"
"\n"
"mydata = 42\n"
"\n"
"    def test_function(mydata):\n"
">       assert mydata == 23\n"
"E       assert 42 == 23\n"
"\n"
"test_caching.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"======= 1 failed in 0.12 seconds ========"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:248
msgid "Clearing Cache content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:250
msgid ""
"You can instruct pytest to clear all cache files and values by adding the "
"``--cache-clear`` option like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:253
msgid "py.test --cache-clear"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:255
msgid ""
"This is recommended for invocations from Continous Integration servers where "
"isolation and correctness is more important than speed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:263
msgid "config.cache API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:265
msgid ""
"The ``config.cache`` object allows other plugins, including ``conftest.py`` "
"files, to safely and flexibly store and retrieve values across test runs "
"because the ``config`` object is available in many places."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/cache.rst:271
msgid ""
"Under the hood, the cache plugin uses the simple dumps/loads API of the json "
"stdlib module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.get:1
msgid ""
"return cached value for the given key.  If no value was yet cached or the "
"value cannot be read, the specified default is returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.get:0 _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.set:0
#: _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.makedir:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.get:5 _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.set:3
msgid ""
"must be a ``/`` separated value. Usually the first name is the name of your "
"plugin or your application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.get:7
msgid "must be provided in case of a cache-miss or invalid cache values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.set:1
msgid "save value for the given key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.set:5
msgid ""
"must be of any combination of basic python types, including nested types "
"like e. g. lists of dictionaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.makedir:1
msgid ""
"return a directory path object with the given name.  If the directory does "
"not yet exist, it will be created.  You can use it to manage files likes e. "
"g. store/retrieve database dumps across test sessions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/cacheprovider.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.cacheprovider.Cache.makedir:6
msgid ""
"must be a string not containing a ``/`` separator. Make sure the name "
"contains your plugin or application identifiers to prevent clashes with "
"other cache users."
msgstr ""
